        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer89081088" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6614069685560559552">This book was masterfully written and extremely surprising. I picked it up off my roommate&apos;s shelf thinking, &quot;Oh, this looks like a sweet little book about spelling bees.&quot; I don&apos;t even know where to begin in describing how wrong I was. That was one thing that made the book so stunning: it completely circumvented my expectations. <br/><br/>The story is complex, with overtones that are varyingly dark and bright and intriguing. I think you could have conversations for hours about the characters in this book-</span>
  <span id="freeText6614069685560559552" style="display:none">This book was masterfully written and extremely surprising. I picked it up off my roommate's shelf thinking, "Oh, this looks like a sweet little book about spelling bees." I don't even know where to begin in describing how wrong I was. That was one thing that made the book so stunning: it completely circumvented my expectations. <br /><br />The story is complex, with overtones that are varyingly dark and bright and intriguing. I think you could have conversations for hours about the characters in this book--their brief perceived brushes with perfection/God, their sense of loss as it slips away, their longing to experience it again, and the isolation that results from their individual obsessions with recapturing that moment of wholeness . . . I gave it 5 stars because I felt like the writing was so very, very good. <br /><br />I would definitely recommend this book, with a warning that its tone of dysfunction is so vivid that it may pervade your personal life as you read it--but I wouldn't let that stop you, it's worth it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6614069685560559552" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
